OBJECTIVE
•	To generate a continuous Square Wave at Port 2 (P2) of an 8051 microcontroller by toggling the logic levels between High (FFH) and Low (00H) with a software-defined time delay.

ALGORITHM

1.	Initialize: Load the Accumulator (A) with 00H (logic low).
2.	Output: Send the value of the Accumulator to Port 2.
3.	Wait: Call a delay subroutine to keep the signal at the current level for a specific duration.
4.	Toggle: Complement the bits in the Accumulator (change 00H to FFH or vice versa).
5.	Repeat: Jump back to step 2 to create a continuous periodic wave.
6.	Delay Subroutine: Use nested loops with registers (R1 and R2) to create a time gap by decrementing their values until they reach zero.

CODE

        MOV A, #00H     ; Start with logic Low
L1:     MOV P2, A    	; Output the current state to Port 2
        LCALL DELAY  	; Stay in this state for a while
        CPL A        	; Complement A (Toggle between 00H and FFH)
        LJMP L1      	; Repeat infinitely

; --- Delay Subroutine ---
DELAY: MOV R1, #05H 	; Load outer loop counter
LOOP:  MOV R2, #0FFH	; Load inner loop counter
L2:    DJNZ R2, L2  	; Decrement R2 until 0
      DJNZ R1, LOOP		; Decrement R1 until 0
      RET          		; Return to main program
		
PROCEDURE

1. Power ON the 8051 Trainer Kit.
2. Enter the program by selecting the A (Address) option and specifying the starting address 4100.
3. Type the assembly mnemonics (MOV, LCALL, CPL, etc.) sequentially into the kit starting from address 4100.
4. Execute the program using the GO command followed by the program’s starting address 4100.
5. Verify the output by connecting the probes of a Cathode Ray Oscilloscope (CRO) to the Port 2 pins and the Ground (GND) pin on the trainer kit’s interface header to observe the square waveform.

EXPECTED OUTPUT

On an oscilloscope connected to any pin of Port 2 (e.g., P2.0), you will observe a Square Wave.
•	Logic High: +5V (Represented by FFH in code).
•	Logic Low: 0V (Represented by 00H in code).
•	Duty Cycle: Approximately 50%, as the delay provided for both the High and Low states is identical.
•	Frequency: Determined by the crystal frequency of the 8051 and the constants moved into registers R1 and R2 (05H and FFH).
